This hands-on course combines a theoretical introduction to Bayesian statistics, case studies from different language sciences, and practical exercises with R.

The course assumes some practical experience with R, ideally in combination with RStudio.

Our main package will be brms. Installing it can be somewhat tricky because it relies on Stan, which is used to fit Bayesian models. 

So please make sure you have it installed before the course starts.

To run Stan, you will also need a C++ compiler available through RTools (Windows) or Xcode (Mac). You can find all necessary information here:

https://github.com/stan-dev/rstan/wiki/RStan-Getting-Started

Once RStan is working correctly, you can install and use brms. 

https://github.com/paul-buerkner/brms

I strongly recommend carefully following all steps described in the documentation. 

You can use this code to make sure if that Stan really works by fitting a model because library(brms) may not raise any warnings or error messages:

install.packages("brms")
library(brms)
set.seed(10)
data <- data.frame(Var = rnorm(100, 20, 1))
model <- brm(Var ~ 1, data = data)
summary(model)

As an alternative, you can run R in Google Colab. However, this setup can be slower and less convenient, especially if you need to load a dataset, so I hope you will be able to use brms in RStudio on your own computer.
